+# 📅 Day 1 — Foundations & Your First Sentiment Prediction
+
+> "A journey of a thousand reviews begins with a single `pip install`."
+
+Welcome to Day 1! Today is about **setting up cleanly** and then writing your **very first AI-powered sentiment script**. Don't worry — by the end of today you will have a working program that reads a sentence and tells you if it's happy or angry.
+
+---
+
+## 🎯 What You'll Learn Today
+
+- How to set up a clean Python virtual environment (and why it matters)
+- What a **pre-trained model** is and why we *don't* train one ourselves
+- How to use the Hugging Face `transformers` library
+- Run your first sentiment classification in under 10 lines of code
+
+---
+
+## 🤔 The Problem
+
+Imagine you run a small online shop. Every morning 50 new reviews come in. You want to know, *fast*:
+
+> "Are people happy today, or angry today?"
+
+Reading them all takes 30 minutes. By the end of today you'll do it in **0.5 seconds**.
+
+But there's a sub-problem: **training an AI model from scratch is hard.** It requires:
+- A huge dataset of labelled reviews
+- A GPU
+- Hours of training time
+- Math we don't want to think about yet
+
+**The trick:** somebody already did all that work and put the model online for free. We just *download and use* it. This is called a **pre-trained model**, and the website that hosts them is **Hugging Face** 🤗.
+
+---
+
+## 💡 The Solution
+
+We use Hugging Face's `pipeline()` helper. It's a one-line shortcut that:
+
+1. Downloads a pre-trained sentiment model (only the first time — then it's cached locally)
+2. Handles all the tokenization, tensors, math
+3. Returns a clean Python dict with a label and a confidence score
+
+That's it. No ML degree required.
+
+---
+
+## 🛠️ Step 1 — Set Up Your Environment
+
+Open a terminal in the `Day-1/` folder and run:
+
+```bash
+# 1. Create an isolated Python environment so we don't pollute your system
+python -m venv venv
+
+# 2. Activate it
+#    On Mac/Linux:
+source venv/bin/activate
+#    On Windows (PowerShell):
+venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
+
+# 3. Install the two libraries we need today
+pip install -r requirements.txt
+```
+
+**Why a virtual environment?** Different projects need different library versions. A venv is like a little sandbox just for this project, so it never breaks another one. Always use one.
+
+---
+
+## 🧑‍💻 Step 2 — The Code
+
+Create a file called `sentiment_first.py` (or just open the one provided here) and look at this 10-line script:
+
+```python
+# sentiment_first.py
+# Day 1: Our very first sentiment analyzer using Hugging Face.
+
+from transformers import pipeline   # 1️⃣ The "pipeline" is a ready-to-use AI shortcut
+
+# 2️⃣ Build the sentiment analyzer.
+#    The first time you run this, it downloads a small model (~250MB).
+#    Every run after that is instant because the model is cached.
+analyzer = pipeline("sentiment-analysis")
+
+# 3️⃣ A few example reviews to try.
+reviews = [
+    "I absolutely love this product, best purchase of the year!",
+    "Worst experience ever. The item broke in two days.",
+    "It's fine. Nothing special, but it works.",
+]
+
+# 4️⃣ Loop through each review, ask the model, and print the result.
+for review in reviews:
+    result = analyzer(review)[0]    # The pipeline returns a list; we take [0]
+    label  = result["label"]        # 'POSITIVE' or 'NEGATIVE'
+    score  = result["score"]        # confidence from 0 → 1
+    print(f"📝 {review}")
+    print(f"   → {label} ({score:.2%} confident)\n")
+```
+
+### 🧠 What just happened, line-by-line?
+
+| Line | What it does |
+|------|--------------|
+| `from transformers import pipeline` | Imports Hugging Face's one-stop helper. |
+| `pipeline("sentiment-analysis")` | Tells HF: *"I want the sentiment-analysis task — pick a default good model for me."* It downloads `distilbert-base-uncased-finetuned-sst-2-english`. |
+| `analyzer(review)` | Sends the text into the model. Internally it tokenises the text, runs the neural network, and returns the prediction. |
+| `result["label"]` and `result["score"]` | The model's verdict and how sure it is. |
+
+That's literally it. You just used a real deep-learning model.
+
+---
+
+## ▶️ Try It Yourself
+
+```bash
+python sentiment_first.py
+```
+
+You should see something like:
+
+```
+📝 I absolutely love this product, best purchase of the year!
+   → POSITIVE (99.98% confident)
+
+📝 Worst experience ever. The item broke in two days.
+   → NEGATIVE (99.97% confident)
+
+📝 It's fine. Nothing special, but it works.
+   → POSITIVE (87.42% confident)
+```
+
+🎉 **Congratulations** — you just ran your first AI sentiment classifier.
+
+### 🧪 Mini-Experiments
+Edit the `reviews` list and try:
+- A sarcastic sentence: *"Oh great, another broken charger. Just what I needed."* — Does the model get fooled? (It usually does! This is *why* we add OpenAI tomorrow.)
+- A mixed sentence: *"Battery is amazing but the camera is terrible."*
+- A non-English sentence — observe what happens.
+
+These limitations are *exactly* the problems we'll fix on Day 2 and Day 5.
+
+---
+
+## 🤓 A Note on the "Neutral" Label
+
+You'll notice today's model only outputs **POSITIVE** or **NEGATIVE** — there's no "Neutral". That's a limitation of this particular default model.
+
+On **Day 2**, OpenAI will give us a real Neutral label.
+On **Day 4**, we'll swap in a better Hugging Face model (`cardiffnlp/twitter-roberta-base-sentiment`) that also supports Neutral.
+
+Small steps. Don't worry about it yet.
+
+---
+
+## 🔭 Tomorrow's Preview — Day 2
+
+Tomorrow we plug in the **OpenAI API**. Why? Because:
+- We want a **third label**: Neutral
+- We want a **reason** — *"this review is negative because the customer mentions slow delivery and a missing accessory"*
+- We want to learn **prompt engineering** — the new "programming" of the AI era
+
+See you on **[Day 2 →](../Day-2)**.
